[
    {
        "content": "<p>Hello there folks. I was recently musing on the fact that all of the interesting limits I know of (or at least interesting enough to be named concepts in their own right) arise from diagrams that have no interesting composition structure. By this I mean that the only composition structure in the relevant indexing category is precisely what is necessitated by the strictures of categoryhood.</p>\n<p>In other words, the limits I know about are really indexed by (the free categories of) graphs. These include terminal objects, products, pullbacks, and equalizers.</p>\n<p>I was wondering if folks can point me to interesting examples of limits arising from diagrams with \"prescribed\" compositions in the indexing category (i.e. where the indexing category is not equivalent to the free category generated by some graph). The simpler the example the better. Thanks!</p>",
        "id": 270096158,
        "sender_full_name": "Asad Saeeduddin",
        "timestamp": 1643659528
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If you view a group action as a diagram <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">B</mi><mi>G</mi><mo>→</mo><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">S</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"bold\">t</mi></mrow></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbf{B}G \\to \\mathbf{Set}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbf\">B</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6861em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbf\">Set</span></span></span></span></span>, the limit of this diagram is the set of elements fixed by all of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>G</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">G</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">G</span></span></span></span> and the colimit is the set of orbits of the action.</p>",
        "id": 270097400,
        "sender_full_name": "Ralph Sarkis",
        "timestamp": 1643660004
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A <a href=\"http://nlab-pages.s3.us-east-2.amazonaws.com/nlab/show/filtered+limit\">filtered limit</a> (such as the stalks of a sheaf) also uses composition nontrivially.</p>",
        "id": 270099522,
        "sender_full_name": "Paolo Perrone",
        "timestamp": 1643660814
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>However, it is true that in a 1-category, the limit of a diagram <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\to D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span> is isomorphic to the limit of the corresponding diagram <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>U</mi><mi>C</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>D</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">FUC\\to D</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.02778em;\">D</span></span></span></span>, where <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>F</mi><mi>U</mi><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">FUC</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.13889em;\">F</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.10903em;\">U</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span> is the free category on the underlying directed graph of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span></span></span></span>.  So in that sense, as long as you remain in the world of 1-categories, the composition structure in the indexing category is \"irrelevant\".  But this fails once you move up to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-categories for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n&gt;1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&gt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> (although I think there is a somewhat-analogous fact that limits in an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-category are determined by simplicial <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-skeleta of indexing categories).</p>",
        "id": 270114722,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1643667412
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/229199-learning.3A-questions/topic/Limits.20of.20diagrams.20with.20interesting.20composition.20structure/near/270114722\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>But this fails once you move up to <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-categories for <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>&gt;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n&gt;1</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.5782em;vertical-align:-0.0391em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">&gt;</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6444em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">1</span></span></span></span> (although I think there is a somewhat-analogous fact that limits in an <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-category are determined by simplicial <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>n</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">n</span></span></span></span>-skeleta of indexing categories).</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I think this can be found in Section 3 of <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/pdf/1910.04117.pdf\">https://arxiv.org/pdf/1910.04117.pdf</a></p>",
        "id": 270127931,
        "sender_full_name": "Ian Coley",
        "timestamp": 1643673731
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span> very interesting. but I'm having trouble identifying why the <code>BG -&gt; Set</code> example does not count as \"1-categorical\"</p>",
        "id": 270147987,
        "sender_full_name": "Asad Saeeduddin",
        "timestamp": 1643687708
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It is 1-categorical, and the composition law of <code>G</code> does not matter--the limit is the set of <code>G</code>-fixed points, and these only depend on the actions of all the elements of <code>G</code>.</p>",
        "id": 270148372,
        "sender_full_name": "Reid Barton",
        "timestamp": 1643687988
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>This discussion reminds me of <a href=\"https://mathoverflow.net/questions/391627/shapes-for-category-theory\">https://mathoverflow.net/questions/391627/shapes-for-category-theory</a>.</p>",
        "id": 270202863,
        "sender_full_name": "Leopold Schlicht",
        "timestamp": 1643719702
    }
]